			When counting in the decimal system, only ten symbols are needed to represent numbers. Numbers are grouped into groups of 10 to make them easier to represent.
			In dozenal, two extra symbols are added on to the existing ten, for a total of 12. After 9, the two new numbers are added, X and E, to make this:
			1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, X, E, 10, ... E9, EX, EE, 100
			

